^x } |HT|j|AT|^c@2
From what hand should the lead be made in order for you to have the maximum likelihood of taking 2 tricks with the Ace and Queen? |
PG| ***** 101 ***** |


CP|8|AT|The answer is that the lead should be made from the hand on your left. |
PG| ***** 102 ***** |


CP||AT|  In other words, if your left-hand Opponent leads that suit, you will be the last to play to the trick, and you will therefore be in a position to win the trick with whatever card is required. In fact, whenever the lead comes from the hand on your left, your expectation of winning 2 tricks with your Ace-Queen tenace becomes a 100% certainty.|
pg| ***** 103 ***** |


cs|4|ht|p|va|6|at|^b{ |ht|u|at|^y
^x } |HT|p|va|6|AT|^c@2
What is the next most advantageous lead? |
PG| ***** 104 ***** |


AT|The answer is that there are two equally advantageous directions from which the lead may come, provided it cannot come from the left-hand Opponent. |
PG| ***** 105 ***** |


CP||AT|You may lead the suit yourself, from the Dummy's hand up to your Ace-Queen. Also, if your right-hand Opponent leads the suit, it comes up to your Ace-Queen with equal advantage. In both situations, your Queen may be finessed; it wins whenever your right-hand Opponent has the King, and loses when your left-hand Opponent has it.|
pg| ***** 106 ***** |


