at|

^*IEvery combination of cards in which one or more honors is missing is but a variation of the Ace-Queen tenace^*N. The direction of the lead has exactly the same effect upon it. Whenever the lead is from the Opponent on the ^*Ileft^*N of the tenace, the tenace has the best chance to win. A lead from the opposite hand is equal in value to a lead from the Opponent on the right of the tenace. |
PG| ***** 113 ***** |


CP|8|FP|2|at|To lead from the tenace itself is the least likely to prove at all profitable. |
PG| ***** 114 ***** |


FP||AT| Every situation that ever arises in the play of the cards, even if it seems different, is governed by this fundamental principle. No matter what different aspect any combination of cards may appear to take, it is only wearing a cloak—you need but apply this principle in some form, and the problem is solved. This will become clearer and clearer as you progress from elementary to advanced play.|
