HT|d|CS|1|cp|4|AT|^-

{    Reflection on the Chapter by Howard Schutzman   }
^-|CS||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^Y@3^*Bhondo717:^*N|cp||at| I do not believe this Chapter needs much expanding. However, here are a couple of points which I always emphasis during our mentoring sessions.|
PG| ***** 119 ***** |


AT|

1) This chapter emphasizes the importance of planning your declarer play, just as I do. Planning how you use your entries to your best advantage is one of the key elements of a successful declarer plan.|
PG| ***** 120 ***** |


AT|

2) The chapter also touches on the reason for second hand low. It demonstrates how being the fourth hand to play to a trick is the most advantageous, because if you cannot win the trick, you can at least play a low card, and not waste a high card to force out an opponent's high card. Third hand is the least advantageous on many tricks, because you have to play a high card to force out a high card from the opponent. Since second hand is the first hand to play to a particular trick, normally second hand should play low, which forces third hand to play high, hopefully allowing partner to capture one of the opponents's honors with a higher honor.|
PG| ***** 121 ***** |


AT|

3) The chapter also alludes to the general principle of how to execute an "end play", an advanced declarer play technique. If you have a tenace you want to protect, and can throw your left hand opponent in and force him to lead the suit with the tenace, you can use your tenace to maximum advantage, because you will be the fourth hand to play on that trick. That is the essence of an end play. The rest is details on how you accomplish that.|
PG| ***** 122 ***** |


